{{Expand Spanish|José Benito Monterroso|date=April 2013}}
'''José Benito Silverio Monterroso Bermúdez''' ([[Montevideo]] 1780-1838) was a Roman Catholic priest from the [[Banda Oriental]], the pre-independence name of [[Uruguay]].<ref name="post">[http://iglesiacatolica.org.uy/la-iglesia-en-la-filatelia/jose-benito-monterroso-franciscano-sacerdote-secretario-de-artigas/ José Benito Monterroso in post stamps] {{es icon}}</ref>

He was ordained in the [[Franciscan Order]] and later became lecturer in [[Philosophy]] and [[Theology]] at the [[National University of Córdoba|University of Córdoba]].

==Uruguayan independence-era patriot==

He was a notable patriot during the fight for freedom in colonial times. He was decisive in the development of Artiguism, the thought of [[José Gervasio Artigas]].<ref name="post"/>

===Family background===

Monterroso was the eldest of six. His sister [[Ana Monterroso|Ana]]<ref name="post"/> married [[Juan Antonio Lavalleja]], leader of the [[Thirty-Three Orientals]].

