{{Infobox religious biography | name = Thomas Henshaw | native_name = | native_name_lang = en | image = Bishop Thomas Henshaw.jpg | caption = Bishop of Salford 1925-1938 | sanskrit = | religion = Roman Catholic | school = | lineage = | sect = | subsect = | temple = | order = | other_name = | dharma_name = | monastic_name = | pen_name = | posthumous_name = | nationality = English | ethnicity = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth date|1873|02|02|df=y}} | birth_place = Manchester | death_date = {{death date|1938|09|23|df=y}} | death_place = Manchester | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = | location = Salford | title = Bishop of Salford | period = | consecration = 21 December 1925 | predecessor = | successor = | reason = | rank = Bishop | teacher = | reincarnation_of = | students = | works = | ordination = | profession = | education = | initiation = | previous_post = | present_post = | post = | website = }}
'''Thomas Henshaw''' (1873–1938) was the fifth [[Bishop of Salford]], a [[Roman Catholic]] diocese in the north-west of [[England]].
==Early life and education== He was born on 2 February 1873 in [[Miles Platting]] in [[Manchester]], the son of Thomas Henshaw, a Manchester coal merchant, and his wife Ann Billington. He was educated at the Salford Catholic Grammar School, the [[English College, Lisbon]], and at [[St Cuthbert's College, Ushaw|St Cuthbert's College]], Ushaw, where he taught French for three years as a Minor Professor.
==Early career== He was ordained priest on 18 October 1899. Following ordination, Henshaw was sent to the [[Institut Catholique, Paris]], where he specialised for three years in [[Dogmatic Theology]]. He then spent a year at [[Bonn University]], before taking the chair in Dogmatic Theology at [[Ushaw College]].
In 1905, Henshaw returned to his native [[Diocese of Salford|Salford Diocese]], serving for the next six years at [[St Bede's College, Manchester|St Bede's College]] as Professor and Vice-Rector. In 1912, he was appointed curate at St Alban, Blackburn until 1913, when he became Rector at the Holy Saviour, [[Nelson, Lancashire|Nelson]]. In 1916, he moved to St Mary, Heaton Norris, and in 1920 took charge of St Gabriel, Castleton. In mid-1925 he was appointed parish priest at St Anne, [[Blackburn]], where he completed the work building the new Byzantine church started by the previous priest, Fr William Shine, who had died suddenly earlier that year.<ref>{{Catholic-hierarchy|bishop|bhens|Bishop Thomas Henshaw|21 January 2015}}</ref>
==As Bishop of Salford== Bishop [[Louis Charles Casartelli]] had died in January 1925, but it would be almost a year before a replacement was appointed. That replacement was Henshaw, consecrated Bishop on 21 December 1925 at [[Salford Cathedral]] by [[Archbishop Keating]]. He was taken as a "pastorally minded and pragmatic parish priest with financial acumen and quiet scholarship".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.salforddiocese.org.uk/history/index.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-05-14 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090502013908/http://www.salforddiocese.org.uk/history/index.html |archivedate=2009-05-02 |df= }}</ref>
Education was Henshaw's forte, even if the vision of Catholic education in Westminster and in Salford occasionally clashed. Particular problems of physically defective "blacklisted" schools and of the beginning of [[slum clearance]] in inner urban areas, taxed the mind and pocket of the Catholic community. The 1936 Education Act separated schools into Junior and Senior Schools and ended, at least in theory, the all-age parish elementary school.
The lay organisations continued to develop, with newcomers such as the [[Legion of Mary]] and the [[Young Christian Workers]]. Henshaw's attitude to the continual shortage of priests was simple: pray and the Lord will provide.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.salforddiocese.org.uk/history/index.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-05-14 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090502013908/http://www.salforddiocese.org.uk/history/index.html |archivedate=2009-05-02 |df= }}</ref>
In 1926 the diocese also hosted the National Catholic Congress in Manchester. In 1927 he acquired the [[Wardley Hall]] Estate in [[Worsley]] as the official residence of the Bishop of Salford
He died on 23 September 1938, aged 65.
