 for details on automatic unit conversion--> |area_water_km2 = |area_total_sq_mi = |area_land_sq_mi = |area_water_sq_mi = |area_water_percent = |area_urban_km2 = |area_urban_sq_mi = |area_metro_km2 = |area_metro_sq_mi = |area_blank1_title = |area_blank1_km2 = |area_blank1_sq_mi = <!-- Population -----------------------> |population_as_of = |population_footnotes = |population_note = |population_total = |population_density_km2 = |population_density_sq_mi = |population_metro = |population_density_metro_km2 = |population_density_metro_sq_mi = |population_urban = |population_density_urban_km2 = |population_density_urban_sq_mi = |population_blank1_title =Ethnicities |population_blank1 = |population_blank2_title =Religions |population_blank2 = |population_density_blank1_km2 = |population_density_blank1_sq_mi = <!-- General information ---------------> |timezone = |utc_offset = |timezone_DST = |utc_offset_DST = |elevation_footnotes = <!--for references: use<ref> </ref> tags--> |elevation_m = 1540 |elevation_ft = }} {{Infobox ancient site |name = Yanta |native_name = |alternate_name = Yanta |image = |alt = |caption = |map_type = Lebanon |map_alt = {{convert|1500|m|ft}} |map_size = 200 |location = north of [[Kfar Qouq]] |region = [[Bekaa Valley]] |coordinates = {{coord|33.603056|35.944167|display=inline}} |type = |part_of = |length = |width = |area = |height = |builder = |material = |built = |abandoned = |epochs = |cultures = [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] |dependency_of = |occupants = |event = |excavations = |archaeologists = |condition = Ruins |ownership = |management = |public_access = Yes |website = |notes = }} '''Yanta''' is a [[village]] situated in [[Rashaya District]], [[Beqaa Governorate]], [[Lebanon]], {{convert|79|km|mi}} from [[Beirut]]. It is located close to the [[Syrian]] border north of [[Kfar Qouq]].<ref name="Furaiḥa1972">{{cite book|author=Anīs Furaiḥa|title=dictionary of the name of towns and villages in Lebanon|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aiUeNAAACAAJ|accessdate=17 March 2011|year=1972|publisher=Maktabat Lubnān}}</ref>
The village sits about {{convert|1540|m|ft}} above sea level. The name is variously claimed to mean "God sows" or "God the sower" in [[Semitic languages|Semitic]], "white dove" in [[Syraic]] and "elevation" in [[Arabic]].<ref>[http://tourism.leb961.com/brochures/rachaya.pdf Qada' (Caza) Rachaya - Promenade Tourist Brochure, published by The Lebanese Ministry of Tourism]</ref> It has been noted that a special type of yellow [[marl]] (lake sediments) has been noticed in Yanta and the surrounding area dated to the [[Oxfordian (stage)|Oxfordian]].<ref name="HombergBachmann2010">{{cite book|author1=C. Homberg|author2=M. Bachmann|title=Evolution of the Levant Margin and Western Arabia Platform Since the Mesozoic|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GGqjUOJ3Aq4C&pg=PA232|accessdate=24 April 2011|date=15 October 2010|publisher=Geological Society|isbn=978-1-86239-306-6|pages=232–}}</ref> In 2001 and 2002, archaeological studies were carried out at [[Kamid al lawz]] near Yanta that unearthed a large amount of [[Ancient Greek pottery]].<ref name="Myers2010">{{cite book|author=E. A. Myers|title=The Ituraeans and the Roman Near East: Reassessing the Sources|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-cRrGQ8bIAkC&pg=PA88|accessdate=24 April 2011|date=31 January 2010|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-51887-1|pages=88–}}</ref>
==Roman temple== There are ruins of an impressively sized and positioned [[Roman temple]] in the area that is presumed to have been built on the site of a forerunning Semitic temple.<ref name="Mannheim2001">{{cite book|author=Ivan Mannheim|title=Syria & Lebanon handbook: the travel guide|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t9LHVdWLc7gC&pg=PA603|accessdate=24 April 2011|date=1 July 2001|publisher=Footprint Travel Guides|isbn=978-1-900949-90-3|pages=603–}}</ref><ref name="Taylor1969">{{cite book|author=George Taylor|title=The Roman temples of Lebanon: a pictorial guide, pp. 22, 127, 130|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XXchNqgyNdkC|accessdate=24 April 2011|year=1969|publisher=Argonaut}}</ref> The ruins lie on either side of the road and are sparse but retain some upright stones. Around the site are remnants of ancient habitation and tombs.
